<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRANSTON'S BILL FOR BONDHOLDERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Your editorial represents the typical reaction of those untouched by this 
affair. It drags out the old caveat emptor defense in the name of saving the 
taxpayers for state and federal official errors and misdeeds. 
</P>
<P>
At the time (while these bonds were being sold) almost everyone was fooled by 
the fast-buck artistry of Keating and his cronies. Except for two or three 
underling regulators, all the principals were fooled -- Alan Greenspan, our Fed 
chairman, five or more senators and countless government agency heads. They 
rushed to help Keating target a select group of savings and loan customers for 
a neat sales scheme. This target of mostly naive elderly were fleeced of their 
life savings by as clever a bait-and-switch operation as I have ever seen. And 
it all happened inside the doors of a supposedly rock-solid, well-regulated 
savings and loan office. 
</P>
<P>
Your editorial puts you in bed with the principals in this case, who looked 
around after it was disclosed and piously said "it wasn't my fault" or "they 
were greedy." Let's face it, we were all fooled and you do a great disservice 
by equating these bondholders with those who buy and sell bonds on the open 
market. Only the small print buried inside the prospectus hints that these 
bonds could never reach the open market and were forever locked inside Lincoln 
Savings. There are too many dirty hands here for a caveat emptor defense. 
Cranston is rightly trying to settle now, instead of later, a case that may 
make the legal profession more wealthy at taxpayers' expense. 
</P>
<P>
WILLIAM LUEDEKING 
</P>
<P>
Laguna Hills 
</P>
