<HEADLINE>
<P>
HIGH SCHOOL ATHLETE OF THE WEEK: DAMEWORTH SETS PACE FOR THE NATION'S BEST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE GLAZE, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Winning. The word has become synonymous with Agoura High distance runner Bryan 
Dameworth. In fact, the last time Dameworth lost a race was in the state track 
and field championships last June when he finished second to David Welsh of 
Sacramento Jesuit in the 3,200-meter final. 
</P>
<P>
Less than two months after conquering the nation's finest high school 
cross-country runners in the Kinney national championships, Dameworth, a 
senior, took his enviable record to the Millrose Games at Madison Square Garden 
in New York City. 
</P>
<P>
The surroundings might have been unfamiliar but not the result. Overcoming a 
case of nerves and a shaky start, Dameworth won the high school mile Friday in 
4 minutes 14.52 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
"Basically, when the gun went off, it was like 'Whoa,' " said the 6-foot-3, 
163-pound Dameworth, who surged into the lead with 640 yards remaining. "It 
took a while to get into the groove." 
</P>
<P>
Dameworth defeated a field that included runner-up Martin Keino (4:16.63), a 
senior at Fork Union (Va.) Military Academy and the son of former Olympic 
champion Kip Keino of Kenya. 
</P>
<P>
It was also win No. 2 indoors for Dameworth, who captured the same event 
(4:17.77) in the prestigious Sunkist Invitational on Jan. 19 at the Sports 
Arena. 
</P>
<P>
There he outdistanced Keino (who finished third in 4:18.78) and Somalian Jama 
Bile (fifth, 4:19.37), younger brother of Abdi, the 1987 world champion at 
1,500 meters. 
</P>
<P>
But the competition on the track took a back seat for Dameworth, who had other 
concerns about visiting the Big Apple on his first trip to the East Coast. 
</P>
<P>
"I was making sure I didn't get killed or anything," he said. 
</P>
<P>
While Dameworth was watching his back, Agoura Coach Bill Duley was at home in 
Calabasas thinking about being with his stepson. 
</P>
<P>
"I stayed home and wondered and waited for the phone call (providing the 
results of Dameworth's race)," Duley said. "I was fine until about an hour 
before his race, then I really wanted to be there." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Bryan Dameworth finished the cross-country season undefeated and his 
success has carried over to the indoor track season. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
