<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: ANAHEIM; 
</P>
<P>
CAR WRECKERS ASK COUNCIL TO OK MOVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LISA MASCARO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Consultants for the Pick Your Part auto-wrecking yard appealed to the City 
Council on Tuesday night after failing to win Planning Commission approval to 
move the operation from Stanton to the site of a former landfill in Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for a group of about 100 residents who oppose the relocation, which 
they said would put the industrial-style operation too near their homes, said 
they expected the appeal. 
</P>
<P>
Phil Steyerman, accompanied by other members of the Stop Pick Your Part 
Committee, said they will again don their yellow T-shirts and show their 
opposition when the council holds a hearing on the appeal. No hearing date has 
been set. 
</P>
<P>
The 20-acre lot is at 2925 W. Lincoln Ave. Most of the homeowners who oppose 
the proposal live in a housing tract north of the site. 
</P>
<P>
Consultants for the company, which must move from its current location by March 
1, had compiled detailed plans for what they called a state-of-the-art 
auto-recycling center, hoping to assure residents that the operation would not 
be a typical junkyard. LISA MASCARO 
</P>
</TEXT>
