<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: RETAIL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Compiled by Mary Ann Galante, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Short sales increase: Just three months after its "grand reopening" to 
celebrate a $100-million renovation, Newport Center/Fashion Island is noisily 
touting its 54% mall-wide sales increase during the 1989 fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
Predictably, mall officials relate the quarterly increase -- representing total 
sales of $77 million or $67 per square foot -- to the renovation. 
</P>
<P>
But considering that Fashion Island added 70,000 square feet of retail space 
for 60 new stores, the upswing isn't too surprising. 
</P>
<P>
Dana Lazzarevich, a mall spokeswoman, said fourth-quarter sales totals without 
the newly added stores were not available. Not counting the mall's anchor 
tenants, including Bullock's Wilshire and Neiman-Marcus, mall sales in the 
fourth quarter climbed 33.4% to $39.9 million from $29.9 million, she said. 
Those numbers, however, also include the new retail footage. 
</P>
<P>
Among Orange County's other malls, preliminary indications are that 1989 
fourth-quarter sales showed modest gains. 
</P>
<P>
Not including anchor tenants, here are the sales tallies reported by some of 
Orange County's top-grossing malls for the last period, October-December, 1989: 
Brea Mall was up 8%; Westminster Mall down 1.5%, and Buena Park Mall up 5.5%. 
Compiled by Mary Ann Galante, Times staff writer 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
