<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE'S PHARMACY: ALL COLD REMEDIES 'WORK' THE SAME -- THEY REALLY DON'T 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOE GRAEDON, AND TERESA GRAEDON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It's a billion-dollar industry that flourishes on misery -- sniffles, sneezes 
and sore throats. But despite the ads on television promising instant relief, 
most cold remedies provide little more than smoke and mirrors. 
</P>
<P>
Antihistamines are a mainstay of the runny nose market. But while they help 
against allergies and hay fever, they are almost useless against the common 
cold. The FDA has been asked to reject antihistamines for cold treatment, but 
the agency has so far avoided the issue. 
</P>
<P>
Pain killers like aspirin and acetaminophen are common ingredients in cold 
remedies. Doubtless, ibuprofen will start showing up in the near future. But 
are such drugs helpful against a cold? 
</P>
<P>
In most cases the answer is no. Garden-variety colds are not generally 
associated with aches and pains or high fevers. If you feel like you've been 
hit by a truck, chances are you have the flu instead of a cold. 
</P>
<P>
What about gargles, sprays and throat drops? None will cure a sore throat or 
really do much to relieve inflammation, which is what causes the pain in the 
first place. A salt water gargle (one-half teaspoon of salt in an 8-ounce 
glass) may provide as much temporary relief as most lozenges. 
</P>
<P>
Oral decongestants such as pseudoephedrine (Sudafed) and phenylpropanolamine 
(PPA), found in Contac, Dimetapp and Alka-Seltzer Plus, can help a stuffy nose. 
They tend to dry out the mouth and nasal passages in the process, though. 
People with high blood pressure, heart disease, diabetes, prostate enlargement 
or an overactive thyroid gland should probably avoid such products. 
</P>
<P>
Nasal sprays that contain topical decongestants such as Afrin, Duration, 
Otrivin or Neo-Synephrine are extremely effective and appear safer than oral 
decongestants, but they can only be used for three days. After that you run the 
risk of developing a dependency because when you stop spritzing your sinuses 
the congestion returns worse than before. 
</P>
<P>
So what should you do if you catch a cold? For one thing, stay home. The first 
few days you will be the most contagious, so don't share it with everyone else. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Elliot Dick, one of the country's leading cold researchers, has become a 
believer in massive doses of vitamin C. To get this vitamin into white blood 
cells where it is needed he suggests several grams a day. 
</P>
<P>
No matter what your favorite treatment -- chicken soup, vitamin C or every pill 
and potion in the pharmacy -- your cold will probably go away in a week. And if 
you take nothing at all it will likely last seven days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA020790-0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 173043 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
February 7, 1990, Wednesday, P.M. Final 
</P>
